{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9d8bf79f-c444-4848-9ea2-9b9e05291297","content":"`SafeAreaEdges` isn't a built-in `ContentPage` property in .NET MAUI — that's likely why it has no effect. Here's what you actually need:\n\n**iOS** — disable safe area on the page:\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\">\n```\n\n**Android** — in your `MainActivity.cs` or platform code, make the system bars transparent so content draws behind them:\n```csharp\n#if ANDROID\nusing AndroidX.Core.View;\n\n// In your MainActivity or startup:\nvar window = Platform.CurrentActivity.Window;\nWindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(window, false);\nwindow.SetStatusBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\nwindow.SetNavigationBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n#endif\n```\n\n> **Note:** On .NET 10 targeting Android 15+, edge-to-edge is enforced by default, but you still need transparent bars.\n\n**Image setup** — use `AspectFill` and remove any margin/padding:\n```xml\n<Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n       Aspect=\"AspectFill\"\n       HorizontalOptions=\"Fill\"\n       VerticalOptions=\"Fill\" />\n```\n\nThe most common missing piece is the **iOS `UseSafeArea=\"False\"`** — without it, MAUI automatically insets content away from the status bar and home indicator.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8ea68fea-cd02-4a78-bb2a-7887563afa64","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making content go edge-to-edge in a .NET MAUI app, going behind the status bar and navigation bar. They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` but still see padding.\n\nThis is a common .NET MAUI question. Let me think about what's needed:\n\nIn .NET MAUI, to achieve true edge-to-edge content:\n\n1. `IgnoreSafeArea` on the view itself - this is often the missing piece\n2. On Android, you need to opt into edge-to-edge mode\n3. On iOS, the safe area insets need to be handled\n\n\n4. I should clarify that `SafeAreaEdges` controls which edges the page respects safe areas for, but individual views might need their own configuration. On iOS specifically, `Page.IgnoreSafeArea` or the platform-specific `UseSafeArea` setting is what allows content to go behind the status bar and notch areas.\n\nFor edge-to-edge layouts in .NET MAUI, the approach differs by platform: on iOS I'd use `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"`, while on Android I need to handle window configuration and system bar transparency, especially since newer versions target edge-to-edge by default. I should clarify that `SafeAreaEdges` isn't a standard MAUI property—they might be mixing up frameworks or using a custom implementation. The real solution involves disabling safe area on iOS with the platform-specific markup, ensuring transparent system bars on Android, and setting the Image to `AspectFill` so it actually fills the screen without constraints from parent layouts.","outputTokens":1226,"requestId":"111A:2C695B:D52E6E:F6F9E0:69FE887B"},"id":"1a5275e7-c6a5-4a18-8454-d32b36214980","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:06:31.047Z","parentId":"51060f2f-68ba-4a9c-b3cd-2ac3153c0947"}
